<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Ollas for Tomatoes in Containers</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Tomatoes don’t need more water — they need more consistent water.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, the best ollas for container tomatoes are medium-sized, unglazed terracotta ollas that match the container size and provide steady, slow moisture release.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Container tomatoes are prone to inconsistent watering. Dry soil one day and overwatering the next can lead to stress, poor growth, and issues like blossom end rot.
  </p>
  <p>
    Ollas solve this by delivering water gradually, directly to the root zone.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Works Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> medium unglazed terracotta olla.</li>
      <li><strong>Best feature:</strong> slow, consistent seepage.</li>
      <li><strong>Best priority:</strong> matching olla size to container volume.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    Size matching is more important than capacity alone.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Ollas Work in Containers</h2>

  <p>
    Ollas are porous clay vessels buried in soil and filled with water. Moisture seeps through the walls as the surrounding soil dries.
  </p>

  <p>
    This creates:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>consistent moisture levels</li>
    <li>reduced watering frequency</li>
    <li>less surface evaporation</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The system responds to plant demand rather than fixed schedules.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Tomatoes Benefit from Ollas</h2>

  <p>
    Tomatoes are sensitive to uneven watering. In containers, soil dries out quickly and can fluctuate throughout the day.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consistent moisture helps:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>reduce stress</li>
    <li>support steady growth</li>
    <li>prevent common watering-related issues</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Ollas help stabilize these conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Good Olla for Containers</h2>

  <h3>Unglazed Terracotta</h3>
  <p>
    Allows water to seep through the surface.
  </p>

  <h3>Appropriate Size</h3>
  <p>
    Must match the container volume and plant size.
  </p>

  <h3>Secure Lid</h3>
  <p>
    Prevents evaporation and debris from entering.
  </p>

  <h3>Compact Shape</h3>
  <p>
    Fits within container without crowding roots.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Size Matching: The Most Important Factor</h2>

  <p>
    An olla that’s too small won’t provide enough moisture. Too large, and it takes up valuable root space.
  </p>

  <p>
    In most cases:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>small containers need small ollas</li>
    <li>larger containers may need multiple or larger ollas</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Balance water supply with root space.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where Ollas Work Best</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>container-grown tomatoes</strong></li>
    <li><strong>hot or dry climates</strong></li>
    <li><strong>gardeners who want less frequent watering</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    They’re especially helpful when consistent watering is difficult.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where They Fall Short</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>very small containers</strong></li>
    <li><strong>frequent rainfall environments</strong></li>
    <li><strong>setups with already consistent irrigation</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    They’re not necessary in every situation.
  </p>
</section>

